  "prompt": "Why do Navy squadrons start with a V?",
  "response": "The \"V\" in U.S. Navy squadron designations stands for \"fixed-wing aircraft.\" This is opposed to squadrons that operate rotary-wing aircraft (helicopters), which typically start with an \"H.\" The use of \"V\" can be traced back to World War II when the designation system was first developed. In this system:\n\n- \"VF\" stands for Fighter Squadron,\n- \"VA\" stands for Attack Squadron,\n- \"VP\" stands for Patrol Squadron,\n- \"VFA\" stands for Strike Fighter Squadron, combining fighter and attack roles.\n\nThe \"V\" helps to distinguish these fixed-wing aircraft squadrons from other types of aviation units within the Navy.",
